data.content:
Here are the key modern MSTest patterns for async testing:

### 1. Async Test Methods

Return `Task` (not `void`) from async tests:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public async Task FetchAsync_ReturnsContent_WhenSuccessful()
{
    // Arrange
    var handler = new MockHttpMessageHandler("expected content", HttpStatusCode.OK);
    var client = new HttpClient(handler);
    var fetcher = new DataFetcher(client);

    // Act
    var result = await fetcher.FetchAsync("https://example.com");

    // Assert
    Assert.AreEqual("expected content", result);
}
```

### 2. Cooperative Cancellation via `TestContext`

MSTest v3+ flows a `CancellationToken` through `TestContext` that fires on timeout. Use it instead of creating your own tokens:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
[Timeout(5000)] // milliseconds — token cancels when this expires
public async Task FetchAsync_PassesCancellationToken(TestContext testContext)
{
    var handler = new MockHttpMessageHandler("ok", HttpStatusCode.OK);
    var client = new HttpClient(handler);
    var fetcher = new DataFetcher(client);

    // Use the framework-provided token — cancelled automatically on timeout
    await fetcher.FetchAsync("https://example.com",
        testContext.CancellationTokenSource.Token);

    Assert.IsTrue(handler.LastCancellationToken.CanBeCanceled);
}
```

### 3. Testing That Cancellation Is Honored

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public async Task FetchAsync_ThrowsWhenCancelled()
{
    var handler = new MockHttpMessageHandler("ok", HttpStatusCode.OK,
        simulateDelay: true);
    var client = new HttpClient(handler);
    var fetcher = new DataFetcher(client);

    using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
    cts.Cancel(); // pre-cancel

    await Assert.ThrowsExactlyAsync<TaskCanceledException>(
        () => fetcher.FetchAsync("https://example.com", cts.Token));
}
```

### 4. Testing Failure Paths

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public async Task FetchAsync_ThrowsOnServerError()
{
    var handler = new MockHttpMessageHandler("", HttpStatusCode.InternalServerError);
    var client = new HttpClient(handler);
    var fetcher = new DataFetcher(client);

    await Assert.ThrowsExactlyAsync<HttpRequestException>(
        () => fetcher.FetchAsync("https://example.com"));
}
```

### Helper: `MockHttpMessageHandler`

```csharp
internal sealed class MockHttpMessageHandler : HttpMessageHandler
{
    private readonly string _content;
    private readonly HttpStatusCode _statusCode;
    private readonly bool _simulateDelay;

    public CancellationToken LastCancellationToken { get; private set; }

    public MockHttpMessageHandler(string content, HttpStatusCode statusCode,
        bool simulateDelay = false)
    {
        _content = content;
        _statusCode = statusCode;
        _simulateDelay = simulateDelay;
    }

    protected override async Task<HttpResponseMessage> SendAsync(
        HttpRequestMessage request, CancellationToken cancellationToken)
    {
        LastCancellationToken = cancellationToken;

        if (_simulateDelay)
            await Task.Delay(Timeout.Infinite, cancellationToken);

        return new HttpResponseMessage(_statusCode)
        {
            Content = new StringContent(_content)
        };
    }
}
```

### Key Takeaways

| Pattern | Rule |
|---|---|
| Return type | Always `async Task`, never `async void` |
| Timeouts | Use `[Timeout]` + `testContext.CancellationTokenSource.Token` |
| Exception assertions | Use `Assert.ThrowsExactlyAsync<T>` (not `ThrowsException`) |
| HttpClient mocking | Subclass `HttpMessageHandler`, don't mock `HttpClient` directly |
